You know, I’m the type of person who actually enjoys sharing my steps to math problems. I like to see how things stack up… or don’t.

To me, it’s always been a form of communication. It doesn’t matter if I got the answer right or wrong, I just enjoy translating, because I’m an A for effort kind of student.

I like seeing the point I slipped so I can get back up, try again, and understand from a new perspective.

I have this approach with life too.

I love experiencing. I love documenting. I love analyzing, and I love expressing. I like to challenge my limits, and I am determined to become the best version of myself, for myself.

… But sometimes I forget I’m still human. I have emotions, I feel things, I get happy, but I also get upset, frustrated, angry, insecure, and so on.

With that, I’m learning it takes time to tune in, to tune up, because fine-tuning is a PROCESS.

It actually takes work. It’s tiring. It requires rest. It also requires vulnerability, patience, forgiveness, and a whole lot of love, and respect for ourselves. It takes SPACE to sit ALONE and unpack, organize, let go, and even grieve, what no longer serves us…

But it’s worth it.

Also, not everyone has the same question to their life assignment. However, you never know when one of your steps might offer clues for another person’s problem.

Lastly, our errors don’t add up, equal, or define our whole.

We live, and we learn, and that’s beauty, of it all. :)

I was going to make an elaborate post relating to how a lot of us probably have messy corners in our homes (aka those “behind the scenes” corners).

But then this happened, and now I want to share a gentle reminder:

When we have the courage to show up as authentically as possible, it’s easier to hold our grounds, because being ourselves is the only way we know how, right?

So whether you have a big ol’ pile you’re still saying “I’ll get to that eventually”, or if you are learning to laugh with the world through the seasons of life, I hope you find the strength to be unapologetically you.

Because the right people, the right opportunities, and experiences meant for you, will find you, and you them.

And remember: Social Media ≠ Real

He became my little shadow. Wherever I walked, he followed…

Pet sitting Kim’s dog turned out to be a whole journey.

Buster and I had our daily morning walks downtown (except that one particularly brisk day).

We traveled, and visited family, and even made new puppy friends… andd also nearly got attacked by a cat (lol).

We took some selfies and tested out dog foods (because he was way too nervous to eat the first couple days).

We even went on daily coffee drive-through runs because I didn’t know which was worse: leaving him alone with his crippling anxiety in an unfamiliar place, or his obvious discomfort from being in the car…

Safe to say, he is a very sensitive doggo. Yet because of this, he is also alert, attentive, and seriously protective (sorry neighbors).

Oh that Buster boy, Bustah Rhymes, Bust-A-Move.

It’s been real.

Thanks little homie for making me feel like less of a lone wolf. 🐾

Don’t you think to understand your “joie de vivre”, or “joy of living” would be to go out there and actually live it to find out?

You can’t calculate and control every move though. You can try.
But life doesn’t always work like that.

At some point you have to let go.

Because part of learning how to fly is learning to trust the journey.

And if you made it all the way to right here, right now, then you have the power to keep propelling towards everything that *actually* sparks AND sustains joy.

Because now, especially now, you are more equipped from life experiences.

You are no longer the same version of you.

You survived.
You are here.

So keep faith in yourself.

Because you deserve to know your “joie de vivre”.

Garlicky Sesame Orange Ginger Vinaigrette:
* 1/2 cup orange juice
* 1/4 cup+ sweet rice vinegar (@marukanvinegar)
* 3 Tbs honey (or sweetener of choice)
* 2 Tbs toasted sesame oil (@spectrumculinary)
* 1-2 Tbs shoyu (@moromishoyu)
* 1/4 cup tahini (@soomfoods)
* 1 small garlic clove
* 2 Tbs fresh ginger, peeled and finely grated 
* Salt and pepper to taste
In a small blender, pulse all ingredients until smooth. Loosen with more vinegar or water as needed. Taste test and adjust salt and pepper to preference. Transfer to the fridge until ready to use (also helps to marinate flavors together).

Salad for Two:
- 3-4 handfuls raw kale, chopped (Remember to massage your kale! Crisp lettuce is a great substitute, don’t massage that though)
- 1 cup carrots, shredded or julienned (or bell peppers, whatever you have)
- 2 large navel oranges, cut into segments, orange membrane reserved
- 1 cup sesame sticks (or preferred salty/sweet crunchy topping)
- 6 small beats, cooked, peeled, and cut into bite-sized pieces (@lovebeets)
- 1/4+ cup pickled red onions
- 1 handful micro greens (@farmingturtles)
- Seed mixture to garnish (optional)
- Pinch of sea salt

Assembly:
1. In a large mixing bowl, add kale, carrots, and squeeze the juice from the orange membrane, compost membrane. Season with a pinch of sea salt, then toss to combine.
2. Divide and transfer the mixture onto 2 large plates. Afterwards, have fun layering orange segments, beets, red onions, and sesame sticks. Drizzle dressing in between layers (trust your gut).
3. Finally, garnish with micro greens and seed mix. Share, and enjoy! :)

P.S. The @thepioneerwoman has a great resource for how to segment an orange.

Almost by default, I am an “influencer” because I create content for a living, which then “influences” people.

Icebox Cookies
 
Yields: ~ 48 cookies
Prep Time: 20-30 minutes
Inactive Time: 3+ hours
Bake Time: 12-15 minutes
 
Ingredients:
- 200g unsalted butter, brought to room temp
- 1 egg yolk
- 1/2 tsp vanilla extract 
- 1/2 tsp sea salt
- 125g powered sugar
- 45g almond flour
- 300g cake flour
 
Method:
1. Using a large mixing bowl, cream the butter using a whisk or fork until light and fluffy.
2. Add the egg yolk and vanilla extract, then whisk until thoroughly combined.
3. In a separate large mixing bowl, sift together all the dry ingredients (cake flour, almond flour, powdered sugar, salt).
4. Afterwards, gradually add the dry mixture into the butter mixture. Stir to combine. Repeat with remainder of dry mixture until a consistent dough forms. 
5. Next, prepare a 24” length of parchment or wax paper, transfer and center the dough onto the paper, then roll into a log, about 2” thick. Twist the ends to seal, then transfer to the fridge for at least 3 hours, or until solidified to the touch.
6. When ready, preheat oven to 350°F. In the meantime, remove and unwrap log of dough and slice cross-width into 1/4” rounds. Transfer the rounds onto a lined baking sheet, placing at least 1” apart.
7. When ready, bake the tray of cookies for 12-15 minutes, or until golden around the edges. Then, transfer the tray of cookies onto a cooling rack.
8. Share and enjoy!

Anyways, here’s my go-to soup recipe. It’s unfussy, because when you’re feeling under the weather, the last thing you want is a complicated recipe or a pile of dishes.

Simple Rotisserie Chicken & Veggie Soup:
Serves: 8
Prep Time: 10 min
Cook Time: 30-ish min

- 1 Tbs avocado oil (or cooking oil of preference) @lesserevilsnacks 
- 2 small zucchinis, diced
- 2 small onions, diced
- 2 large stalks celery, diced
- 2 large carrots, peeled and diced
- 1” knob fresh ginger, peeled and minced
- 3+ cloves garlic, minced
- 1/4 tsp turmeric powder
- 2 Tbs herbs, chopped (rosemary, sage, thyme)
- 3 cups kale, chopped
- 1-2 lemons
- 2 Tbs @betterthanbouillon (vegetable base)
- 1 rotisserie chicken, bones removed, roughly chopped
- 4-6 cups water 
- S&P to season

1. Bring a large pot to medium heat and add oil. Add the onions, celery, and carrots, then season with salt and pepper. Sauté until softened, about 10-12 minutes.
2. Afterwards, add turmeric, garlic, ginger, and herbs. Stir, then cook until fragrant, about 1 minute.
3. Add the kale and cook until just wilted, about 3 minutes, then add chicken.
4. Pour water to cover, then add bouillon. Stir to combine, taste test, and adjust to preference.
5. Next, bring the soup to a boil, then reduce to a simmer. Cover, and cook for 15 minutes. When ready, finish with fresh lemon juice, taste test again, and adjust as needed. Finally, share and enjoy!

P.S. I love to finish with @tastyafhotchilioil for added umami and heat!

A recipe for Star Crossed Lovers

Strawberry Raspberry Vanilla Lemon Compote:
- 1 cup raspberries
- 1 cup strawberries, halved and sliced
- 3 Tbs water
- 3 Tbs granulated sugar
- 1 tsp lemon zest
- 1 tsp lemon juice
- 1 tsp Vanilla Extract

1. In a small saucepan, combine berries, sugar, water, lemon juice, and zest. Bring to medium heat, and cook for 8-10 minutes, stirring frequently until fruit softens, and mixture thickens. When ready, allow to cool completely before using, at least 30 minutes.

Star Crossed Lovers Cocktail:
- @legrandcortage Brut Rosé, chilled
- Strawberry Raspberry Vanilla Lemon Compote, chilled
- Pineapple Juice, chilled

1. In a wine glass, add ice, then layer 1/3 of the cup with berry compote.
2. Layer 1/3 of the cup with pineapple juice, then finish with brut rosé. Gently stir, garnish to preference (we used orchids), and enjoy! Cheers!

Getting vulnerable here…

I was so emotionally overstimulated the other day I could barely focus on moving anything. My Mom was helping me unpack the cabinets, and I never knew I could make so many jokes to self sooth… or sob so defeated in anyone’s arms.

Though, afterwards, I was finally able to open my eyes to see and recognize just how many people actually care about me and want to pour into my cup, because at some point or another, I poured into theirs too, whether I was aware of it or not.

Through that, I finally found the roots of my imposter syndrome and a handful of other insecurities, along with the trauma I was carrying from the people before me.

It’s been painful (I never got a response from the therapist I reached out to, but I also knew I didn’t have time to wait for someone to validate me through my emotional rollercoaster). They don’t call it growing pains for nothing. I guess that’s also why they say, when it rains, it pours.

That said, this reel is a symbolic reminder of the importance of finding the light within.

In doing so, it helps us solidify and secure a foundation for whatever adventures our next chapters hold.

It feels like I am finally relinquishing control of the pen to my story, and leaning into trusting the journey a little more.

I wouldn’t feel this way without the help and support of the communities both online and offline.

- 3 Tbs Granulated Sugar
- 1 tsp lime zest
- 1 tsp lime juice
- 1/2 tsp Vanilla Extract

1. In a small saucepan, combine blueberries, sugar, water, lime juice, and lime zest. Bring to medium heat, and cook for 10 minutes, stirring frequently until thickened. Stir in vanilla extract. When ready, allow to cool completely before using.

Blueberry Tie Dye Cocktails (for 2):
- 3 oz @tccrafttequila Blanco
- 1/3 cup Blueberry Lime Compote, chilled
- 6 oz Pineapple Juice, chilled
- 1.5 oz lime juice 
- .5 oz ginger juice
- 1-2 Tbs raw honey
- Ginger Seltzer

1. In a shaker, add ice, tequila, pineapple juice, lime juice, ginger juice, honey, and blueberry compote.

Cheesy Tteokbokki

Serves: 4
Prep Time: 10-12 min
Cook Time: 12-18 min

* 2 lb. Korean rice cakes
* 1 Tbs cooking oil
* 2-3 garlic cloves, minced
* 1 cup Korean sausages, sliced (optional)
* 2 1/2 cups soup stock
* 3 spring onions, chopped into 3” pieces
* 2 tsp toasted sesame oil
* 1 cup low moisture mozzarella, shredded

Tteokbokki Sauce
* 2 Tbs gochujang (Korean chili paste)
* 1 1/2 Tbs gochugaru
* 2 Tbsp granulated sugar (more or less to preference)
* 1 Tbs oyster sauce
* 1 Tbs shoyu (soy sauce)
* 1 Tbs Mirin

Method:
1. Unless rice cakes are soft already, soak in warm water for 10 minutes.
2. Meanwhile, using a small mixing bowl, stir together tteokbokki sauce ingredients until consistent. Set aside.
3. Bring a large pan to medium heat, add cooking oil, garlic, and sausages. Stir to combine and cook until golden and fragrant, about 3-5 minutes.
4. Return the sauce to the pan along with water. Stir until the sauce dissolves, then increase heat to medium high. Once boiling, add the rice cakes. Boil for 5 minutes, or until soft and cooked thoroughly.
5. Reduce heat to medium, then simmer for an additional  2-5 minutes to allow sauce to thicken (as starches release from the rice cakes).
6. When ready, add the sesame oil and green onions, then stir to combine. Top the tteokbokki with an even layer of shredded mozzarella, cover pan with a lid, and reduce heat to low. Cook for a 2-3 minutes, or until cheese melts.
7. When ready, turn off heat, uncover, and garnish with parsley (optional). Serve warm, share, and enjoy! :)

I had a nightmare.

It’s probably been a year since my previous one.

It dawned on me: Last year I went through a string of traumatic events.

(I’ll spare the details)

I decided to dig deeper.

What was my unconscious trying to to tell me? What was my insecurity beneath the discomforting visuals?

Eventually I realized, as a result of what I went through, I became afraid of being so disconnected from myself that I allowed valuable moments and life experiences pass me by with eyes wide open.

I became afraid, because I inherently knew I wasn’t as connected to myself as I wanted to be.

And the problem wasn’t not wanting to be connected, the obstacle was:

I didn’t understand how I even got there… because in actuality, I was still processing grief.

In hindsight, it turns out grief isn’t something you place a band-aid on, nor something you simply “get over” or breeze past.

Grief is something that requires and demands time, space, and personal grace, to comprehend.

And when we don’t fully process that, it can take a toll on not just the mind and the spirit, but the body too.

Yet grief is something all of us will, or have already faced. It’s an inevitable part of life.

But like anything else, no matter what we go through, our character and integrity reveals itself when we react to circumstances beyond our control.

It is how we show up in spite of the unknown, how we show up for ourselves, and how we show up for the people we love and still have, as well as those we have yet to meet.

That said, If you are going through something, please don’t be afraid to let go of the pain of loss.

Be more afraid of losing the ability to experience joys this life continues to gift.

Please, be here.
Even if imperfectly, be here.

Because the past doesn’t need you. This present moment does.

So feel your feels. But bridge yourself back to your body, develop systems to ground yourself, and be courageous when releasing what does not sit well with your soul. Strengthen your mindset…

For you still have a story to live.
You still have a journey to share about.
And you still have plenty of love to give.

So again,
Please,
Be here.

Keep going.

All I’m sayin’ is grilling season isn’t over yet, and this recipe got me through a good deal of meal preps ;)

Chicken Satay Lettuce Wraps with Peanut Sesame Dressing (Sans Skewers):

Prep Time: 15 min
Inactive Time: 2+ hrs
Cook Time: 10-15 min

Marinade:
- 1 lb. Chicken thighs or breasts, boneless skinless
- 1/2 cup coconut milk
- 2+ garlic cloves, minced or grated
- 1 Tbs fresh ginger, minced or finely sliced
- 1 stalk lemon grass, thinly sliced
- 1 Tbs sugar
- 2 tsp curry powder
- 1 tsp sea salt
- 1/2 tsp cracked black pepper
- 1 tsp fish sauce
- 1 Tbs sriracha (optional)

Dressing:
- 1 lime
- 2 Tbs smooth peanut butter, unsweetened
- 2 Tbs rice vinegar
- 1 tsp fish sauce
- 2 Tbs honey
- 1 Tbs toasted sesame oil (I used a chili version, but not necessary)
- 1 garlic clove, minced or grated
- 1-2 tsp sriracha (optional)

Assembly:
- 1 small head butter lettuce, leaves separated into cups
- Scallions, thinly sliced (optional)
- Chopped nuts (optional)
- Fermented Thai chili sauce (optional, recipe coming soon)

1. In a large mixing bowl, add all ingredients except chicken thighs, and whisk to combine.
2. Place chicken thighs in the marinade and stir to coat, making sure all pieces are submerged. Cover, then transfer to the fridge to marinate for 2-4 hours.
3. In the meantime, prepare the dressing. Add all ingredients into a small airtight jar with lid. Cover, then shake until well combined. Taste test and adjust as needed. Refrigerate until ready to pair.
4. When chicken is ready to grill, remove from the fridge and fire up the grill. Bring to high heat (or a steady 450°F). Grill for 10-15 minutes, flipping halfway through until thoroughly cooked, or until internal temperature reaches 165°F. Remove from heat, then allow to rest for a minutes(to help lock in juices.)
5. Meanwhile, arrange lettuce cups. Slice chicken into strips, then divide amongst lettuce cups. Return the dressing and drizzle on top or pair alongside. Finish with scallions, Thai chilis, and chopped nuts (optional). Enjoy!

Kimchi Fried Rice

Serves: 6
Prep Time: 5 min Cook Time: 15-20 min

* 2 Tbs cooking oil
* 1” knob ginger, grated or julienned
* 3 cloves garlic, minced
* 3 shallots, sliced
* 1 cup spam, diced (or protein of choice)
* 3 stalks green onions, sliced (darker green bits reserved for garnish)
* 1 1/2 cups mixed veggies, chopped into small pieces (carrots, peas, whatever you have on hand)
* 1/2 cup kimchi
* 2 Tbs gochujang
* 2 tsp toasted sesame oil
* 1/4 cup fried shallots
* 2 large eggs, whisked
* 2 cups cooked jasmine rice, preferably day old
* Toasted sesame seeds (optional)

1. Bring a large heavy-bottomed skillet to medium heat. Drizzle 1 Tbs of cooking oil. Add the garlic and ginger, then sauté until golden, about 1 minute. Add the shallots and spam, then stir to combine. Cook until shallots wilt and edges of meat begin to brown, 3-5 minutes.
2. Next, push contents to edges of skillet and add kimchi, cook 1 minute before stirring together. Then, add mixed veggies and green onions. Stir to combine, cook 1-2 minutes.
3. Afterwards, add gochujang, toasted sesame oil, and fried shallots. Mix evenly, then push contents to edges of skillet. Add another 1 Tbs cooking oil to the center, then pour in eggs. Stir until just scrambled, then mix altogether, 1-2 minutes.
4. Then, add cooked rice and stir altogether to combine. Increase heat to medium-high, smooth and press the fried rice into skillet. Cook 3-5 minutes, undisturbed, to crisp and create crispy golden bits from the pan surface.
5. When ready, remove from heat and give a final stir before serving. Garnish with sesame seeds and green onions (optional). Share, and enjoy! :)

It showcases touches of oak, layers of fresh raspberries, cherry, cedar, spice, and wrapped with aromas of vanilla, while their Rioja Blanco is crisp and bright, zingy, with hints of white almond and melon, along with aromas of peaches, apples, and citrus.

Both pair especially well with grilled food.

Because of this, whenever I taste their wine, it brings me back to a summer feeling…

That said, I would love to hear your thoughts on this wine too!

Cheesy Tteokbokki

Serves: 4
Prep Time: 10-12 min
Cook Time: 12-18 min

* 2 lb. Korean rice cakes
* 1 Tbs cooking oil
* 2-3 garlic cloves, minced
* 1 cup Korean sausages, sliced (optional)
* 2 1/2 cups soup stock
* 3 spring onions, chopped into 3” pieces
* 2 tsp toasted sesame oil
* 1 cup low moisture mozzarella, shredded

Tteokbokki Sauce
* 2 Tbs gochujang (Korean chili paste)
* 1 1/2 Tbs gochugaru
* 2 Tbsp granulated sugar (more or less to preference)
* 1 Tbs oyster sauce
* 1 Tbs shoyu (soy sauce)
* 1 Tbs Mirin

Method:
1. Unless rice cakes are soft already, soak in warm water for 10 minutes.
2. Meanwhile, using a small mixing bowl, stir together tteokbokki sauce ingredients until consistent. Set aside.
3. Bring a large pan to medium heat, add cooking oil, garlic, and sausages. Stir to combine and cook until golden and fragrant, about 3-5 minutes.
4. Return the sauce to the pan along with water. Stir until the sauce dissolves, then increase heat to medium high. Once boiling, add the rice cakes. Boil for 5 minutes, or until soft and cooked thoroughly.
5. Reduce heat to medium, then simmer for an additional  2-5 minutes to allow sauce to thicken (as starches release from the rice cakes).
6. When ready, add the sesame oil and green onions, then stir to combine. Top the tteokbokki with an even layer of shredded mozzarella, cover pan with a lid, and reduce heat to low. Cook for a 2-3 minutes, or until cheese melts.
7. When ready, turn off heat, uncover, and garnish with parsley (optional). Serve warm, share, and enjoy! :)

It’s so cliche but pictures really do say a thousand words.

When I reflect on this image from 2 years ago I flash back to that day and the stories it holds.

Chef Paul and I met through Edible Nutmeg, a local food magazine I landed my first cover with.

Through an image of jewel-toned beet hummus atop a neighboring potter’s speckled ceramics, adorned with seasonal produce, and delicate edible flowers that I drove an hour to acquire (long story short… I was a determined little sh*t, and I still can be at times…)

Anyways, I digress.

From there, Chef Paul found me and we got in contact. Before we knew it I was photographing him in action in this incredible mansion.

That was also the day I met René. I remember how fascinated I was with the florals and herbs he carefully snipped then respectfully laid in an organically organized method amongst the hand-woven splint basket.

In that moment, my camera became an extension of my curiosity and little was holding me back from slipping into flow state so effortlessly…

Which leads us to this image:

Balance.

That’s the first word that comes to mind each time.

There’s this slightly off-center light fixture separating the two sides of the scene. Generic box o’ Joe in the foreground, with papers, chargers, and cups scattered across the surface. Beside lay my first leather camera bag slouched against the chair joining the cluster of objects that weren’t serving any of our priorities at the time. Behind it, an orchestra of food prep shimmied over the island, as the windows framed the two chefs simultaneously yet individually in action, as if in a way that made one ponder the differences in overlapping livelihoods the personalities share…

And then there’s the story between the lines.

That’s my favorite part.

It’s like the photographer’s secret viewpoint. 

Because like any form of expression, there’s something deeply personal about it,
Which the viewer may never understand.

All they have is their interpretation, and perhaps they even feel a spark, but maybe not, because all our perceptions and glimpses of reality are vastly unique, kind of like a kaleidoscope in motion.

I guess all this to say…

I’m in awe by it all.

"Sed omnia praclara tam difficilia quam rara sunt"

Translation: All things excellent are as difficult as they are rare.

I’ll never forget this day, the insightful existential conversations the three of us shared, and the recharging spark that carried forward perseverance.

Thank you both ▪️🐑🏴‍☠️🥂

If I’m being honest with myself,
2023 taught me a handful of weird lessons.

It taught me, you can “have it all”, but it’s going to cost you in unfamiliar ways.

It taught me that you can love what you do yet still burn out.

It taught me that if you fizzle, the recovery time is far more mentally, physically, emotionally exhausting than if you just listened to your fatigue. Also, feeling guilty for establishing boundaries does not speed up the healing process.

That year I met a new level of bitterness in myself that I am not proud of, however it helped raise self awareness.

It taught me that the people who still stick around despite these difficult phases are your people. They are family. And the power of community is such a profound gift. Give back as much as possible.

It taught me that just because you are nice and kind in the world, no one owes you that in return. Stay kind anyways. Be the one that breaks patterns. It’s a powerful thing to switch a smile onto someone’s face. You never know what someone is going through.

That year taught me that you can be both grateful and unsure. That you can have positive and negative emotions simultaneously, and that duality is a part of the multifaceted experience of existing in this multidimensional world…

But the most valuable lesson 2023 taught me:

You will never live and learn if you are too paralyzed by fear to experience and immerse in the magnitude of possibility.

That said, I pray 2024 awakens and greets us with so much love that our eyes cannot help but glisten from gratitude.

May 2024 be everything we didn’t know we needed ♾️🩶

I hope this life treats you well.
I hope you get to taste and explore.
I hope you get to travel through food, through literature, through music, through all your senses, through boundless amounts of culture that coexist amongst this planet.
I hope you get to live a life you cannot wait to show up for, even if the grandest moments are tucked between the tiniest pockets of time…
For life, and its limitless possibilities, is too short,
For those brave enough to experience before their clock runs out.
